\"Rule of thumb\":
The table on the right provides a simple statistical rule of thumb for the following question:

"Based on the count of partnerships - what F90D % do I need to see for it to be statistically significant"

Essentially a tool to help you determine if the sample is too small to have a confident takeaway.

We've provided two bounds:

LOW: If my sample is X, I need to see a number LOWER than what is shown in the low column to conclude that this pairing performs WORSE than average..
HIGH: If my sample is X, I need to see a number HIGHER than what is shown in the High column to conclude that this pairing performs BETTER than average.

Very important note for people self-serving (i.e. looking at the raw data without an analysis from the Data team)
Confidence level of 99% translates to "There is a 1% chance that this result came from randomness". In the matrix provided, there are almost 1300 metrics, meaning that we would expect about 13 of them to show significance as a result of randomness. Due to this, please interpret the results by looking at the adjacent data. I.e. if a score of Low shows significance and yet the Very Low of the same trait shows nothing - it is most likely due to chance.
